V1: Proposal for Hardware-Accelerated CQs in RISC-V IOMMU

Jiankang Chen
Jan 23   #254  

Author

Shuai Xue alibaba

Jiankang Chen alibaba

Ren Guo alibaba

Introduction

The current RISC-V IOMMU specification defines a single Command Queue (CQ) interface, which becomes a critical bottleneck in high-performance computing environments. This proposal presents solutions to address these limitations while maintaining backward compatibility with existing implementations.

Motivation and Problem Statement

Scalability Challenges in Multi-Core Systems

In modern server SoCs with high core counts (e.g. EPYC Turin, up to 192 cores), the single command queue protected by a spinlock creates a severe serialization bottleneck. When multiple CPUs simultaneously issue IOTLB invalidation commands, lock contention leads to:

  • Performance degradation proportional to core count
  • Increased latency for memory management operations
  • Poor scaling of I/O-intensive workloads

Virtualization Overhead

Current virtualization support requires a trap-and-emulate model where:

  • Every guest command submission triggers a VM exit
  • The hypervisor must intercept, validate, and proxy commands
  • Each operation incurs significant overhead

AI and HPC Workload Requirements

Contemporary data center, AI, and high-performance computing workloads place unprecedented demands on IOMMU architectures. These requirements go beyond traditional device isolation to enable new computational paradigms. Usage cases:

  • Guest IO-protection
  • Shared Virtual Memory (SVM) Applications inside VMs: Modern AI frameworks (NVIDIA CUDA, AMD ROCm) require unified address spaces between CPU and GPUs
  • DPDK support inside VMs

Industry Standards and Prior Art

Solutions to Single Command Queue Contention

SMMUv3.3-ECMDQ Optional[3] support for Enhanced Command queue interfaces to solve the lock contention. HiSilicon Kunpeng and Marvell SoCs implements SMMU ECMDQ feature and saw ~5% improvement compared with SMMU with software batching support. [1]

NVIDIA's Tegra241 (Grace) SoC has a CMDQ-Virtualization (CMDQV) hardware that extends standard ARM SMMUv3 to support multiple command queues with virtualization capabilities. CMDQV also allows the kernel to use multiple VCMDQs, giving some limited performance improvement: up to 20% reduction of TLB invalidation time was measured by a multi-threaded DMA unmap benchmark, compared to a single queue.[2]

Solutions to Virtualization Overhead

Hardware-assisted virtual IOMMUs have emerged as the industry solution for eliminating trap-and-emulate overhead by providing each guest with dedicated command queue resources.

NVIDIA's Tegra241 (Grace) Virtual Command Queue [2] enables direct guest command submission with a focused set of supported commands, allowing the IOMMU hardware to directly access guest-owned queue memory. This approach yields substantial performance improvements: DMA unmap tests demonstrate 70% to 90% reduction in TLB invalidation time compared to traditional nested SMMU implementations that require hypervisor trapping.

AMD vIOMMU, available since the 2nd generation AMD EPYC (Rome) platform, provides comprehensive hardware acceleration through three dedicated buffers—Command Buffer, Event Log Buffer, and PPR Log Buffer [4]. Each buffer allows guest VMs to directly control hardware queues without hypervisor intervention. Production measurements reveal dramatic performance gains: storage workloads achieve 1.67x higher bandwidth (FIO random read), while network throughput increases by 3.49x (NETPERF TCP_STREAM) compared to virtio-IOMMU implementations [5].

These implementations share a fundamental principle: IOMMU hardware directly accesses guest-controlled queue memory, eliminating VM exits for common operations. The consistent performance improvements across vendors—from 1.67x to 3.5x for real workloads—demonstrate that hardware acceleration is essential for competitive I/O performance in virtualized environments.

Proposed

Solution: Multi-Queue & VCQs

We propose extending the RISC-V IOMMU architecture to support Multiple Hardware Command Queues(CQ) with virtualization capabilities.

Key Mechanisms:

Multiple physical CQs: The hardware provides multiple physical CQs (VF_PARAM.VINTF_NUM_VCMDQ), allowing parallel command execution and priority handling. Each physical CQ has two 64KB MMIO pages (128B per logical VCMDQ):

  • Page0 (directly accessed by guest) has all the control and status bits (cqh, cqt, cqcsr).
  • Page1 (trapped by VMM) has guest-owned queue memory location/size info (cqb). 

    The physical Command Queue (CQ) pool is flexibly allocated to vIOMMU interfaces (VFs). Each VF serves as an allocation unit dedicated to a single virtual machine. Physical Command Queues(CQ) are allocated to vIOMMU interfaces in the form of Logical Command Queues (LCQs) and mapped to LCQs and vIOMMU interfaces. VFs are equipped with configuration mechanisms for managing parameters such as GSCID and RID.

  • Logic CQs(LCQ): In VF, we introduced logical CQ support for mapping physical CQs, where each logical CQ maps to a unique physical CQ. The Page 0 and Page 1 register layout of Logical CQ is the same as physical CQ.
  • Multiple logic CQs support in one VF: To improve the performance of the virtual machine, we allow a single VF to have multiple logical CQs, which in effect means allowing this VF to have multiple physical CQs.
  • Hardware-Enforced Isolation:
    • Each VF is configured by the Hypervisor and bound to a specific GSCID (Guest Soft Context ID) and/or PSCID. The IOMMU hardware automatically tags commands from a VF with these IDs and ensures a VF can only invalidate entries matching its bound VM context.
    • VF serves as a VM management unit, used to configure information
      • Each VF contains a configuration register for a GSCID.
      • Each VF contains a set of VRID to RID mapping: When a VM submits a command containing a VRID, the IOMMU hardware can find the physical RID through mapping.
    • Command Submission: A VF exposes a memory-mapped CQ ring buffer. The Guest OS writes commands directly, bypassing the Hypervisor.
    • VF configuration settings: The VM must trap to the hypervisor to set GSCID, VRID, and LCQ configuration information into the VF configuration registers
    • A VF is only used by a single virtual machine.
  • The kernel and the virtual machine are compatible: In all VFs, VF0 is reserved for kernel use, and the rest of the VFs can be used as virtual machines;

VF, LCQ and CQ mapping relationship diagram:

Control flow and data flow diagrams：

4.2 Register Design

4.2.1 capabilities reg

The RISC-V IOMMU capabilities now include a CAP.VF field (bit 42) to indicate that the RISC-V IOMMU supports VCQ capabilities.

4.2.2 IOMMU VF cap register

  • The RISC-V IOMMU VF cap register adds a field named feat.CQ_NUMs(bit 0~15) to indicate the number of supported CQ.
  • The RISC-V IOMMU VF cap register adds a field called feat.VF_NUM(bit 16~31) to indicate the number of supported VF.
  • VF_CAP: vf vrid register group

Register name

Bit fileld

Meaning

Description

VF_CAP

[31:16]

CQ_NUM

physical cq queue number

VF_CAP

[15:0]

VF_NUM

VF number

4.2.4 LCQ page0 registers layout

CQ registers layout is similar CQs (refer to section 6.6, 6.7 and 6.8). In RISC-V IOMMU multi-CQ, to the CQ there are many CQs in the queue pages, each of which has a set of registers as follows:

name

size

description

CQ_HEAD

4B

hold queue head index

CQ_TAIL

4B

hold queue tail index

CQ_CSR

4B

control the operations and report the status of CQ

  • CQ_HEAD: HEAD register format for each CQ register. Refer section 6.7 Command-queue head (cqh) for details.

  • CQ_tail: Tail register format for each CQ register. Refer section 6.7 Command-queue tail (cqt) for details.

  • CQ_CSR: CSR register format for each CQ register. Refer section 6.15. Command-queue CSR (cqcsr) for details.

4.2.5 LCQ PAGE1 

To ensure address space isolation and security, CQ's address configuration registers are located separately on page 1

name

size

description

multiCQ_BASE

8B

base address

CQ_BASE: Base address register format for each CQ register. Refer section 6.7 Command-queue base (cqb) for details.
